article.headline: Washington 71, Washington State 67
article.story: SEATTLE (AP) -- Will Conroy was in tears when this one was over. "When (Shami) Gill stepped on the end line, I was like, 'Here we go again, man. Here we go again," Washington's emotional junior guard said after the Huskies overcame a six-point deficit in the final minute to edge Washington State 71-67 Thursday night. After taking a pass from Conroy in the corner, muscular 6-foot-8 forward Mike Jensen sank a 3-pointer with 19.9 seconds left to put the Huskies ahead to stay at 69-67. It was the Huskies' eighth victory in their last nine Pac-10 games. "I was having kind of a tough game, but everyone was saying, 'Keep your head up and keep shooting if you get a chance," said Jensen, a starter who had five points and four rebounds in 21 minutes. Jensen credited Conroy's pass with setting up the game-winning shot. "Will did his thing," Jensen said. "He drove a little bit and kicked it out to me. I just shot it in rhythm. As soon as it left my hand, I knew it was good." Huskies coach Lorenzo Romar liked what he saw of Conroy in the final minute. "He had a tough time out there tonight," Romar said. "He made more turnovers (four) than he would have liked, but he came back in crunch time. He is a gamer." Conroy didn't try to hide the fact that he cried openly after the game. "It was just like I couldn't keep the tears from falling down, man," he said. Washington (13-9, 8-7 Pac-10) swept the Cougars for the first time since the 2000 season. The Huskies won in Pullman last month. Jensen's critical 3-pointer put Washington ahead after Washington State (11-13, 5-9) appeared to have the game wrapped up after two free throws by Thomas Kelati, with 1:04 left, gave the Cougars a 67-61 lead. But Conroy sank a 3-pointer with 57.9 seconds to go for Washington and Bobby Jones made a layup with 45.2 seconds on the clock for the Huskies that cut the Washington State lead to 67-66. Jensen got his opportunity to be the hero when Gill stepped on the end line to turn the ball over to the Huskies with 28.2 seconds left. The heartbreaking loss was the third in a row for the Cougars, who lost to Oregon in overtime in their last start last weekend. First-year Cougars coach Dick Bennett said Washington's defensive strategy to contain Marcus Moore was a good one. Moore, his team's top scorer, had 13 points on 5-for-15 shooting. "They took the ball out of Marcus' hands," Bennett said. He said the Cougars lost because they turned the ball over down the stretch. "It boils down to our inability to handle the basketball, deal with the pressure that they put on and our inability to make big plays down the stretch," he said. Moore couldn't believe the Cougars lost the game. "It's a real tough one to swallow," he said. "You think you have the game won and then you lose like that. It doesn't matter how good you play for 39:30. If you fall apart in the last 30 seconds like we did, the rest of the game really doesn't mean anything." Kelati missed a 3-point attempt with 6.8 seconds left and Conroy was fouled by Gill after getting the rebound. Conroy then made two free throws to complete the scoring for the night. Kelati led Washington State with 24 points, including six 3-pointers, both career highs. For Washington, Conroy and Bobby Jones led the way with 15 points each, while Brandon Roy added 13 points and Tre Simmons had 12 points, all on 3-pointers. Washington State trailed 34-30 at halftime, but built up 8-point leads at 59-51 and 61-53.
